types:
dpkg: for Debian-based distributions
apt: a newer frontend for dpkg system found in Debian-based distributions such as Ubuntu
rpm: for redhat distributions such as CentOS

5 modes of rpm:
1. installation    $ rpm -ivh blabla.rpm
2. uninstalling    $ rpm -e blabla.rpm
3. upgrade         $ rpm -Uvh blabla.rpm
4. query           $ rpm -q blabla.rpm
5. verifying       $ rpm -Vf <path-to-file>

rpm doesnt resolve package dependencies, it would be done by YUM package manager.
$ yum install <package-name>        eg. sudo yum install firefox -y
$ yum repolist
$ yum provides <command-name>      //list packages which provide a specific command
$ yum remove <package-name>
$ yum update <package-name>
$ yum update                      //update all packages


5 modes of dpkg:
1. installation/upgrade          $ dpkg -i bla.deb
2. uninstalling                  $ dpkg -r bla.deb
3. list                          $ dpkg -l bla
4. status                        $ dpkg -s bla
5. verifying                     $ dpkg -p <path-to-file>
